Apple posted a sales increase for the all-important holiday quarter, ending=
 a recent slump that had been one of the company=E2=80=99s worst earnings s=
treaks in more than two decades. On Thursday, Apple reported revenue of abo=
ut $120 billion, up 2.1% from the October-to-December period a year earlier=
, and net income of $34 billion, up 13%. Both of those figures exceeded ana=
lyst expectations, according to FactSet. Apple=E2=80=99s crucial iPhone bus=
iness grew nearly 6% from the same year-ago quarter, with $69.7 billion in =
sales versus the $67.6 billion analysts had projected.

This number was more impressive than it seemed given that last year had an =
extra week in the quarter. However, last year also had COVID-related supply=
 chain shortages, which pushed sales to the first quarter of 2023; Apple wi=
ll lap the resultant inventory catch-up this quarter. What is more concerni=
ng is China:

In China, Apple=E2=80=99s third-largest market, revenue declined by about 1=
3% to $21 billion, missing analyst estimates. China has been the most conce=
